04674nam a22007215i 9780813561707DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2012040307  a97808135617077 a10.36019/97808135617072doi  a(DE-B1597)526410  a(OCoLC)857769852  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aLC3727b.P24 2013 4aLC3727b.P24 2013eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a378.1 98292231 aPark, Julie J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhen Diversity Drops :bRace, Religion, and Affirmative Action in Higher Education /cJulie J. Park. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (214 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Cultural and Organizational Contexts of Race, Religion, and Higher Education -- t2 .Changing a Culture: IVCF Decides to Make Race Matter -- t3. Pursuing Common Goals: Building Congruence between Race and Faith -- t4. “Man, This Is Hard” : The Possibilities and Perils of Interracial Friendship -- t5. Shifting Strategies : Going Ethnic-Specific -- t6. When Race Goes on the Backburner: IVCF Loses Diversity -- t7. When a Minority Is the Majority: Asian Americans in IVCF -- t8. Renewing a Commitment : Realigning Values, Structures, and Practice -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJulie J. Park examines how losing racial diversity in a university affects the everyday lives of its students. She uses a student organization, the InterVarsity Christian Fellowship (IVCF) at “California University,” as a case study to show how reductions in racial diversity impact the ability of students to sustain multiethnic communities. The story documents IVCF’s evolution from a predominantly white group that rarely addressed race to the most racially diverse campus fellowship at the university. However, its ability to maintain its multiethnic membership was severely hampered by the drop in black enrollment at California University following the passage of Proposition 209, a statewide affirmative action ban. Park demonstrates how the friendships that students have—or do not have—across racial lines are not just a matter of personal preference or choice; they take place in the contexts that are inevitably shaped by the demographic conditions of the university. She contends that a strong organizational commitment to diversity, while essential, cannot sustain racially diverse student subcultures. Her work makes a critical contribution to our understanding of race and inequality in collegiate life and is a valuable resource for educators and researchers interested in the influence of racial politics on students’ lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAffirmative action programs in educationzUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 0aMulticulturalismzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356170740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813561707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813561707.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK